					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drchandra" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1956625); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1956625&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164535" alt="DrChandra" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1956625)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drchandra" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1956625); return false;" >DrChandra</a></span> <span class="odate time_1509849650 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">05 Nov 2017 02:40</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3626359">
									

<p><a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2718">What Happens After</a> is the scip you're thinking of, and it was the inspiration for this as well as the soul-traps in <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-3440">SCP-3440</a>. I also briefly allude to Retrocausal Quantum Resurrection in <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/Freak-commodities-ii-freak-harder">Freaky Commodities II</a>. It's a horrifying concept and I'm milking it dry.</p>
<p>Though the intent of 2718 was that this is what happens to everyone, you have to ignore or discredit all the other afterlife scips, which doesn't make sense to me. Instead, my headcanon is that O5-11's condition was a result of the specific method of resurrection used. It was stated to involve quantum effects, and therefore had a retrocausal effect on the subject.</p>

							</div>

								
					
